                     ) calculated theoretically (solid line in blue) as well as from experimental data (dashed line in blue) with molar fraction of ethanol (χOS
                     ) collected for the water-ethanol binary mixture. Normalized PL emission spectra of CQDs with molar fraction of organic solvents (χOS
                     ) dispersed in aqueous binary mixture of EtOH (e) and THF (f), the corresponding linear regression plot of PL emission peak positions of CQDs dispersed in aqueous binary mixture has been shown in insets of (e) and (f) respectively.

ce:abstract-sec.ce:simple-para:
Recently studies on synthesis and fluorescence based sensing in biocompatible carbon quantum dots (CQDs) have become a widely spoken topic of research due to the several advantageous properties of CQDs in compared to semiconductor quantum dots. In this work, we have reported the rarely reported solvatochromism along-with a high photoluminescence (PL) quantum yield (PLQY) of 22%. Samples have been synthesized by using a simple process of hydrothermal carbonization of a naturally occurring bio-waste i.e. Aegle marmelos leaves powder. The linear absorption and PL emission characteristics of CQDs have been studied in different solvent environments to explore the origin of the observed excitation dependent PL emissions characteristics of the sample. The interesting solvatochromic PL (SPL) behavior of CQDs are observed at an excitation wavelength of 325nm by dispersing them in different polar protic and aprotic solvents, which suggest their possible applications as a replacement of solvatochromic dye molecules for sensing applications. Different polarity functions and molecular-microscopic solvent polarity parameter (ET
                        N
                     ) are used to calculate the change in dipole moment (Δδ) of the solute-solvent system and the origin of SPL in CQDs has been explained. The SPL behavior of CQDs has been utilized for fluorescence sensing of organic liquids (Ethanol and Tetrahydrofuran) in water. Whereas, the photo-induced electron transfer mediated quenching in PL of aqueous dispersion of CQDs has led to development of “turn off” fluorescence Fe3+ ion sensor with a detection limit of 0.12μM. Therefore, this work may open a new avenue of conversion of a bio-waste into a fluorescent bio-asset.

ce:section.ce:para:
However, the linear behavior of solvatochromic shift in PL emission center of synthesized CQDs (with a typical concentration of 0.1mgmL−1) in aqueous binary mixtures of EtOH and THF at a lower molar fraction has been successfully utilized to demonstrate the possible application of the CQDs as a solvatochromic fluorescent sensing probe for water miscible organic solvents by using the “mix and detect” protocol [3]. The room temperature PL emission spectra collected at an excitation wavelength of 325nm, presented in Fig. 5e–f. It has been found that there is a gradual red shift (in terms of energy) in the PL emission center of the CQDs with increase in molar fraction of organic solvents (i.e., EtOH and THF) present within the aqueous binary mixture. Furthermore, the sensitivities of the synthesized luminescent nanoprobes used for the detection of EtOH and THF in the aqueous mixture have been estimated from the relative PL emission peak position (Ep/Ep0
                           ) vs. molar fraction (χOS
                           ) plot (in Fig. 5e–f). Where, Ep
                            and Ep0
                            are the PL emission peak positions of the CQDs dispersed in an aqueous binary mixture of organic solvents and in bare water, respectively. A linear variation in relative emission peak position with χOS
                            has been observed with correlation factors of 0.9906 and 0.9705 for aqueous binary mixtures of EtOH and THF respectively. Importantly, the limit of detection (LOD) has been estimated from the linear regression fitting as shown in insets of Fig. 5e–f and it is found out to be a molar fraction of 0.9% and 1% for THF and EtOH, respectively.

And interestingly, it is found from Fig. 6e (ii) that the experimental data obtained in the concentration range of (20˂ [Fe3+
                        ]≤250μM) fits very well (R2

                        =0.9926) with the Eq. (12). The summary of the results of fitting are provided in the Table S5 (in Supporting information). It has been found from the Fig. 6c that there is saturation in PL quenching takes place for Fe3+ concentration at above 250μM. This is explained as follows. At very high concentration, such as at >250μM, photon absorption is dominated by Fe3+ than that of CQDs thus saturation in PL quenching has been observed [74].
